name: Lindsey Wheeler
bio: Curated Gifts of Hope || My deep desire is that you know God sees you. He loves you. And there is purpose in your pain! (Psalm 56:8) #bottleoftears

social_posts.post_text: It’s way past midnight and I can’t sleep. Grief is super tricky and nights feel like ten years long sometimes. I’ve tried to write a post all week and just couldn’t even think of anything (mainly because our daughter’s life is hard to explain in words). But, y’all…the grief. It’s felt all-consuming in the past few months. I had someone say to me recently, “you and Chris make trauma look like an adventure.” (One of our biggest family goals is to bring Eliana joy through little trips and adventures…she is her best self on a trip). Chris and I are so determined to keep living and loving and choosing joy even when our world feels so small and sad and hopeless at times. It’s a choice we both make each morning (not every morning but we try). The pics I post of us are the good moments…and we will celebrate the heck out of those moments. Just know most of our moments don’t look beautiful. It’s me crying in bed saying “how long Lord?!”…it’s Chris driving Eliana 2-3 hours a day every single day because it helps her stay calm…it’s walking on eggshells and feeling loneliness like we never have in our lives. On Thursday night of last week Chris prayed “God please bring us hope.” And I woke up and heard Annie’s podcast talking about how we choose to hope in our hard. I needed to hear her words about us to remind me to get up and keep pressing forward. If it’s hard to choose hope, welcome. If you are lonely, know I’m praying for you. God sees us. He does. I am holding tight to that tonight. 🤍

“This is our great hope at Christmas, and the hope we have to share with those who are grieving at Christmas — that ‘yonder breaks a new and glorious morn.’ The Christ who came as a baby and died as our substitute will one day return to consummate his kingdom. And when he does, ‘he will wipe away every tear from their eyes, and death shall be no more, neither shall there be mourning, nor crying, nor pain anymore’ (Revelation 21:4).” — Nancy Guthrie
AMEN 🙌🏽

"Let the beloved of the Lord rest secure in Him, for He shields him all day long, and the one the Lord loves rests between His shoulders." Deuteronomy 33:12b // tag a friend who needs this tonight! Love y’all and praying for you!

There have been moments of 2022 where I wasn’t sure I’d make it…and I mean that. But, this man right here has been a rock for me (and Eliana). I feel like I should apologize for not sharing much over the last few months…but it’s part of this season. Just know I am SO grateful for y’all…and watching y’all love your friends and family through Bottle of Tears gives me so much hope and purpose. 😭
Thinking of you all and praying for you during this holiday season 💙

A really incredible story from my father-in-law (Chris’s dad)…here are his words from Christmas morning:

“Here are the two of us standing in front of the new Jeep Grand Cherokee that God gave us today.  I’m not sure how to tell this story.  So I’ll just recount what’s happened. For months Mary Helen and I have been praying about our transportation needs.  The 2000 Mitsubishi I was given over 10 years ago had become so unreliable that I had stopped driving it.  I could never be sure it was going to get me back from wherever I had gone.  So Mary Helen and I had been taking turns using her car.  It wasn’t convenient, but we were making it work.  We had even talked about just settling for having only one car.  We didn’t want to incur the cost that would be involved in the purchase of a second vehicle - not even a previously owned vehicle that would be “new” to us.  So we kept asking God for wisdom and for His provision. 

Today … Christmas Day … a couple in our church who were aware of our situation drove their 2022 Jeep Grand Cherokee over to our home and gave us the keys!  They said, “It’s yours.” They would never want to be identified and I will not disclose their names.  I’ll just say, we’re overwhelmed!  I never would have imagined that we would have such a vehicle to drive.

Many years ago, I heard a Bible teacher say, “God always gives His best to those who leave the choice to Him”. I’ve experienced that truth again and again.  Christmas 2022 has brought another demonstration of that truth into our lives. Whatever your situation may be, you can be sure the One who sent His Son into this world for us all knows every detail of your need.  Not only does He know what you’re facing, He cares for you.  And it’s true … He always gives His best to those who leave the choice to Him.” -John

Inside each vintage bottle is a beautifully designed art print of Psalm 56:8. "You keep track of all my sorrows. You have collected all my tears in your bottle. You have recorded each one in your book." Each and every bottle is gift wrapped in a kraft box with a note that explains the heart behind Bottle of Tears. Also, there is a card which can be personalized to the recipient.

Together. That’s THE word I think of when I see this pic…we’re together, period. We’re together in the heartache, together in the joy, together in the loneliness, together in the questioning, together in the hope that God is writing a better story. As Walt Whitman said, “We were together, I forgot the rest.” I’d rather be in this together with you Lindsey than anywhere else.

Love you- Chris

“For those who love God—whether that love is great, small, or just clinging on—God works all things together for good. As we grasp this, we realize that the Lord won’t waste a moment of the pain and suffering that often feels pointless and random to us.” ― Kristen Wetherell
Tag a friend who needs this tonight 💙

This necklace features a dainty teardrop shape with a checkerboard faceted natural gemstone in a simple bezel setting, dangling from a delicate chain with a spring ring closure. 

Each necklace is hand-packed in a gift box with a note that explains the heart behind Bottle of Tears. Such an intentional way to show someone that you care about them.

A lot of the last few days were hard…very hard. But, we had this moment of fun and I’m so glad I captured it. And these words I read below made me cry…yes to all of it. 💙

“One thing I know for certain is, 
If I had to do it all again, I would.

If I knew everything that I know now and I knew exactly what I was in for, I would raise my hand and say ‘pick me!’

If I had to do this life over, I wouldn’t swap any little details. 

If I had to choose between this life and a far less complicated one, I would choose you.

Over and over again, 

I would choose you.

-Christine x Special Soul Mama”

“It is in the dark that God is passing by. The bridge and our lives shake not because God has abandoned, but the exact opposite: God is passing by. God is in the tremors. Dark is the holiest ground, the glory passing by. In the blackest, God is closest, at work, forging His perfect and right will. Though it is black and we can't see and our world seems to be free-falling and we feel utterly alone, Christ is most present to us...” ― Ann Voskamp

Eliana texted us from school a couple of weeks ago “I want to play Lacrosse!” She didn’t know a single girl on the team…and she didn’t even know what Lacrosse meant. But, she did it. And we are so proud! Who knows how long this will last…but we will celebrate like crazy! Would y’all pray she catches on quickly…and that she would make a friend on the team?! #elianatheoneandonly

Whatever you are going through as you read this, you need to hear these words: God sees you, He loves you, and your story is not over. Every tear you shed is precious to Him. Your suffering is not in vain.

Happy 19th anniversary to the love of my life…to the man who keeps me laughing especially on the hardest days. I wouldn’t want to walk this road with anyone else!! We are the best teammates ever. Praying for many more years at your side!! 💙 Proverbs 14:13
“Some days He will do far more abundantly than all I can ask or imagine. And other days, He will sustain me in the storm.” — Vaneetha Rendall Risner

We had a couple of hours of fun at the Hogs game after a really really hard week! Thankful for neighbors that offer up their tickets, a few hours of peace for Eliana and getting outside the house! Would y’all pray for a good week for E…and perseverance for Chris and me?! How can I pray for you this week!
"The steadfast love of the Lord never ceases; his mercies never come to an end; they are new every morning; great is your faithfulness." — Lamentations 3:22-23

Today, we sat with each other in our grief. We were witnesses to each other’s deep deep pain. We are so lonely…Chris said “but we are lonely together.” Our sweet girl is in a season that’s truly heartbreaking. And when you have a child like E, you don’t get asked to hang out with other families…and then Chris and I can leave her with a babysitter only a couple of times a year if we are lucky. Our world is very small because that’s all she can handle. We are tired and sad. We love people…love them. And our lives don’t allow us to be with people. I have a hard time posting or sharing on any social media because I know I sound depressing. But, Chris and I decided today we have to keep sharing…because I know SO many of you are walking different but similar roads. You are living out stories that will never have a big red bow on them this side of heaven. We need to keep hoping and praying for each other. Goodness, we need y’all.

This little teardrop plushie and print make an adorable gift set for a little girl or boy in need of hope! Each gift set is hand-packed in a gift box with a note that explains the heart behind Bottle of Tears.
Tag a friend who needs this tonight 💙

"Use your trials and troubles to draw closer to Me. Whenever you start to feel distressed, turn that around by talking with Me. Let pain and problems remind you of your constant need for Me. Create a collection of brief prayers, such as: Help me, Jesus. Fill me with your Peace. Show me Your way." — Jesus Calling

“Even in laughter the heart may ache and the end of joy may be grief," Proverbs 14:13.

This is our family verse. It is a full-hearted acknowledgement that joy and sorrow, good and bad go hand in hand. We shouldn't be shocked by the horrors nor obsessed with the delights. Rather, we just keep moving forward - clinging to the mercy of Jesus each day.
-Chris

(This pic was from our 19th anniversary…we had one night of so much joy. A stranger took this and said “hey, I want to send you a pic I took because y’all look so happy!” But, y’all, the honest truth is nearly every day before and after have been unbearably hard for the last few months. We are still standing ONLY because of Jesus and your prayers).

One minute at a time. 🤍

She doesn’t get a lot of “wins”…so watching E see her name on the JV Cheer roster for next year just about did us in!!! We are SO proud of her…the week was very hard in a lot of ways, but she pushed through. We are praying this will be a good fit for our sweet girl, but no matter what…we are cheering her on! 💙
Chris and I keep reminding each other of this…and I want to remind you of this tonight!! Let’s hope for each other.
Celebrating our nephew’s birthday tonight and the fact we are showered and out of the house! 🤍

I took this pic last weekend at my mom’s house that was hit horribly by the Little Rock tornados. I stood in the backyard and cried and reminisced about so many memories at the house. All around is complete destruction. Chris said the neighborhood looked like a war zone (and it did). Nearly every tree was gone…but look what remained standing in the backyard. It was a light post my grandfather had since my mom was a little girl. I’m going to be super honest (I try to be real on here), I really feel like this old light post. I’m standing tall, I don’t feel or look great, there is hard all around me…but God is not done with me yet. I know I’ve been quiet on here. My heart has been grieving deeply through everything we’ve gone through this year. But, I really don’t want to give up. Would you pray for hope for these families that have lost so much and strength for Chris and me as we continue to fight for joy and hope each day!! Grateful for y’all. 🤍
“Even though I walk through the darkest valley, I will fear no evil, for you are with me; your rod and your staff, they comfort me.” Psalm 23:4 💚
“Blessed are you, dear one, searching for someone to understand, to see your wounds and your hope for healing. You are seen, as you walk this hard and lonely road.” -Kate Bowler 🤍
I need this reminder about twice a day…🤍

These are the faces of two people barely hanging on…Chris likes to say “we are swinging from vine to vine.” The season we are walking through just keeps getting harder. We keep looking at each other and reminding each other that God is in this and He hasn’t forgotten us or our Eliana. Chris breaks out in prayer all day long…that’s all we know to do. Most days, I can barely get out of bed because the depression feels like it’s smothering me. How can someone have joy and also feel like they are dying a slow death of grief…because that is me 24/7 right now. Would y’all pray for our family…goodness there is so much hard right now all around us. Thankful this life is just a mist.
“So with you, Now is your time of grief, but I will see you again and you will rejoice, and no one will take away your joy.” 💜

Lindsey is the absolute most perfect Mom for Eliana.  She was hand selected by God to play this role in Eliana's story. Lindsey literally lays down her very life each day to demonstrate pure love to Eliana. Lindsey's patience is unrivaled. Lindsey’s joyful longsuffering is the stuff of legends. Lindsey's uncommon grace and unique thoughtfulness is truly stunning. Every single day Lindsey chooses to be kind and loving to Eliana (and myself), despite constant fatigue and relentless pain. One of my favorite things about Lindsey is her ability to genuinely honestly say, "it's going to be okay." Her confidence in God's provision and ultimate plan is incredibly comforting to me. 

Thank you Lindsey for your example. I know this day is full of complicated emotions and has an undercurrent of grief. In the midst of the storm, I  honor you today, for your ferocious hope and eternal perspective. Happy Mother's Day.

Love, Chris

So so good from Diane Langberg…”The mourner tells you what they feel and think.  You do not teach.  You listen; you bear witness; you read her and you reassure because you understand the nature of grief.”

“Always take your cues from her. By instinct she is leading, in patience you are serving.”
-Walter Wangerin

We hung out on our neighbor’s back porch last night and it was pure joy…a small break from the hard! God has given us huge reminders this week that He hasn’t forgotten us and I’m so thankful. I texted a friend today that I feel a little bit of light coming and I’m hanging on to it!

“We were under great pressure, far beyond our ability to endure, so that we despaired of life itself.
Indeed, we felt we had received the sentence of death. But this happened that we might not rely on ourselves but on God, who raises the dead. He has delivered us from such a deadly peril, and HE WILL DELIVER US AGAIN. On him we have set our hope that he will continue to deliver us, as you help us by your prayers. Then many will give thanks on our behalf for the gracious favor granted us in answer to the prayers of many.” 2 Corinthians 2:8-11 🤍

Summer is hard. There is no easy way to say it. We have a precious almost 16 year old that will not and cannot stay with anyone else but Chris and me. We are her everything…and y’all, everything sometimes feels like we are very trapped. She isn’t sleeping. We are on eggshells (again, not her fault). We met Chris’s parents in Branson for a weekend trip a few days ago. I got so sick I drove myself to the ER without Eliana ever finding out…and then I drove straight from the ER on pain meds to Silver Dollar City in 92 degrees heat because she needed me to show up. That night I read this from Amanda Held Opelt and cried: “Have you ever felt like you had to rewrite your story of struggle to include redemptive language? Have you ever felt like you had to edit out the most painful parts because you wanted a tidy ending to the story? You can testify to God’s goodness without minimizing your losses. You don’t have to make the bad thing good. You can let it be what it is: bad. Yes, Christ is able to turn mourning into dancing, to infuse hope into hopeless situations. But we don’t have to prove our trust by erasing our sorrow or pretending we are fine.”

Friends, we are desperate for your prayers.

P.S. Playing LIFE has been JOY for her in the last few weeks. So, we will play a lot of rounds!

These words are SO GOOD from Kate Bowler: A blessing for the life you didn't choose…

Blessed are you when the shock subsides,
when vaguely, you see a line appear that divides before and after.
 
You didn’t draw it, and can barely even make it out.
But as surely as minutes add up to hours and days,
here you are,
forced into a story you never would have written. 
 
Blessed are you in the tender place of wonder and dread,
Wondering how to be whole when dreams have disappeared and part of you with them,
where mastery, control, determination, bootstrapping, and grit,
are consigned to the realm of before (where most of the world lives),
in the fever dream that promises infinite choices, unlimited progress, best life now.
 
Blessed are we in the after, loudly shouting: is there anybody here?
We hear the echo, the shuffle of feet, the murmur of others
asking the same question, together in the knowledge
that we are far beyond what we know.

Show us a glimmer of possibility in this new constraint,
that small truths will be given back to us. 
We are held. 
We are safe. 
We are loved. 
We are loved. 
We are loved.

And best of all: We are not alone.

“I didn’t know how much I needed this week…” were Chris’s words on Friday night after a week with some of the most amazing men at @refuge_foundation. I have watched Chris remain steady, faithful, joyful, patient, and fun during the hardest year of his life. Every day feels like we are in a war (and it’s not our sweet daughter’s fault). But, y’all, I’ve never seen a dad like him ever. EVER. The exhaustion, the tears, the pleading with God for healing for our girl, the indescribable trauma, the long nights, the longer drives, the loneliness, the isolation, the longevity of this road, the many hours of doctors and specialists, the researching, the not being able to do “typical” parent things, the fears for the future (or really fears for each day), the walking on constant eggshells, the never having a break, the scary volatility. This is our normal. And praise God Chris got five days to breathe and be prayed over and be seen and loved unconditionally from these incredible men. He said in a text a couple of days ago “God is renewing me for this next year of being her Dad.” Thank you God. 😭

Eliana,

I can hardly believe you are turning 16 years old.  I absolutely love YOU with all of my heart, and I love being your Dad.

I cherish our daily drives around town, and I am so honored to get to talk critters with you each night. Thank you for trusting me with your imagination and creativity. I marvel at your magic. Seeing you laugh is one of the greatest delights of my life.

Your heart is so precious and tender. I love how you include everyone and always want to ensure no one is left out. I see how brave you are each day as you face your fears head on and push through hard things.

Mom and I are so grateful for you and are so blessed to get to be your parents. As we always say in this triangle family, family sticks together - forever.

Happy Birthday, we love you,
Dad and Mom

P.S. God has incredible plans for your life - we can’t wait to see what He writes for your story this new year!
…even if it feels like He has. 🤍

A little over a month ago, we were driving and I prayed silently “God, I would love to see a rainbow.” It was kind of a desperate…”where are you in our story God?” kind of prayer. And y’all, about 5 minutes later…we were nearing our house when I saw it. A full (double) rainbow! And right when we drove up to our house, this is what I saw. It looked like the rainbow was directly touching our roof. It felt like a glimmer of hope. Walking with our child this year has taken everything from us…in every way. And the last three days have been excruciating…so I’m posting this as a reminder to myself today. God sees me…and He sees you.

“Each person’s grief is as unique as their fingerprint. But what everyone has in common is that no matter how they grieve, they share a need for their grief to be witnessed. That doesn’t mean needing someone to try to lessen it or reframe it for them. The need is for someone to be fully present to the magnitude of their loss without trying to point out the silver lining.” -David Kessler 🤍

We’ve had more loss this year than I know what to do with some days. That is the thing with being a parent of a child with a profound, volatile disability with not many answers and no end in sight. We are a lot. Chris and I have dreams…big dreams, but Eliana comes first and occupies most of the space in our brain right now. We are living in the in-between with no red bow at the end of our story. But, I refuse to give up hope that God has BIG things for our girl (and for us). Would y’all be praying for hope for us tonight…for endurance…for more answers and doors being opened. Thank you for continuing to care for your friends with sending them gifts even when I’m horrible at posting in this season. I’m so grateful for y’all. 🤍

Our beautiful Eliana made it through her first week of 10th grade and we couldn’t be any prouder. She has so much to navigate because the school is HUGE. Before school started, she finally got her dream come true…a nose ring. And now she looks a million times cooler that Chris and me. 🤣 Would y’all pray for peace over her mind…FUN for her…and friends that “see” her! (And now that I’ve slept nearly all week, I’m hopeful that I will be more active on this account. Summer was a lot of survival)!
The best gift in the world for my 44th birthday today. 😭 (And yes, I am going to frame it).
Thankful for this reminder tonight. 🤍

We are sticking together…side by side. There is no one I’d rather cry with or laugh with. There is no one that points me to Jesus like Chris. This last year has been so full of loss and pain and grief…but also, God has shown us over and over and over that He is our provider. That He sees us. We are hanging tightly to that tonight. 💙 Thanks for praying for our fam even when I can’t share all of the details. We love y’all.
Your tears matter. 🤍
“You don’t really know Jesus is all you need until Jesus is all you have.” -Tim Keller

This world Chris has created for Eliana BLOWS me away every single day still. Each animal has a very intricate backstory and life…and the stories are hilarious. These animals have helped with so many fears…tears…and talking about things that are hard to do with anyone face to face. This week Eliana couldn’t handle that she got to have dress up days at her high school for homecoming and they didn’t…so she created dress up days for them. And true to Chris’s creativity, he’s made this week so much fun for her!! The last couple of weeks have been particularly hard for her (and me if I’m honest) watching adorable teens dressed up going to dances with their friends (which please keep posting). She has said over and over “mom, I wish someone would ask me to our dance with a poster board.” 😭 And that hasn’t happened. But, God knows her heart and her story and we are determined to make her life as fun and hope-filled as we can in the middle of all of the hard! So, happy homecoming to E and her Critters!
15 years ago today our sweet Eliana became a Wheeler!! 💙 We love her with everything we’ve got.

I really don’t want to write this, but Eliana’s new friend from this year (who is very, very similar to Eliana in so many ways) is moving on Saturday. 😢 Our E’s heart is broken and so is her friend…there are so many things in her story that make this move difficult. We prayed for years for a friend for Eliana and God answered with Gabby. They had two months of making memories and laughing and being kids. And we are just so sad. Would y’all pray for Gabby as she moves…for protection, hope and people to really “see” her in her new city…and for God to provide another friend for E. School is going to be so lonely for her now! Thanks y’all.
So good…and so true. 🤍

Eliana’s dream came true today!! She has BEGGED us for a taxidermy raccoon for years…and I’m not joking! (She really would love a pet raccoon). So, today we bought her this little guy and I’ve never seen her happier!! Everyone was either freaked out thinking she was carrying a live raccoon or laughing their heads off at her and the raccoon. She was a main attraction of Silver Dollar City all day! (Also, she is adamantly against hunting, but in her mind it’s still real…so she’s okay with this). 🤣 She is truly Eliana the one and only!

SURVIVOR FAYETTEVILLE 2023 🔥 “In This Game, Fire Represents Your Life. When Your Fire's Gone, So Are You." -Jeff Probst

Our fave show, our fave show host and how we feel after this past year!! 💚

“There is a sacredness in tears. They are not the mark of weakness, but of power. They speak more eloquently than ten thousand tongues. They are the messengers of overwhelming grief, of deep contrition, and of unspeakable love.” -Washington Irving 🤍

I’m really so tired it hurts. Eliana has NOT had a good week (to put it mildly). I’ve cried and begged God for hope and stared up at my ceiling instead of sleep. Being a parent of a child with a disability is beautiful and scary and hard…but being a parent of a child with a volatile disability will never be easy. Never. Chris and I keep reminding each other to breathe. We do our best this side of heaven to help bring joy into E’s very tormented brain (that is not her fault). We work hard to show people her heart…because it’s so dang beautiful. But, most of our life (it feels like about 98% of the time) is walking on eggshells and trying to remain present and searching for help and trying desperately to see hope when it feels hopeless. I go back and forth on what to share and what not to share, but I want to help other parents in a similar story to not feel alone. Because this is one of the loneliest roads in the world. There are no breaks. There are no weekend getaways with Chris (or one night for that matter). Tonight, I’m sad. Tomorrow morning, I will wake up and choose joy. And hear me, it is a choice. Chris and I love y’all. We are so thankful that you love our family…some of you care about us and we’ve never even met in person. That is God’s kindness to us. One minute at a time.
New print and one of my favorite verses! 🤍
Tonight was a few hours of fun and JOY (that felt like a mini miracle)…and I’m thanking God for laughter, a Christmas parade and time with family! ♥️
NEW Angel Wing Ornament in the shop now! 🪽

This pic was taken a year ago during one of the hardest seasons of our lives. I look at it and cry because it all feels like a big blur. That is what trauma will do to your memory. But, the one constant and joy in this past year has been Chris. His joy isn’t fake…it’s deep joy made out of deep sorrow. The two of us have some fun things coming up…and there is no one I’d rather walk this with than him. 🦘

God saved my life this weekend…and I am still in shock. In a matter of two hours in my sleep Thursday night my throat completely closed up. I wouldn’t have made it if I didn’t go to the ER when I did. It’s been a very long, hard few days. I was immediately put on a ventilator and sedated and by God’s grace am home. The doctors believe I had a very rare bacterial infection that attacked my throat. I’ll be honest, I’m battling anxiety being home because there is not a concrete answer. But I just keep thanking God over and over and over that I’m alive. Would love your prayers as I rest this week…and I’ll post later all that God did in the chaos. Love y’all! (This pic was when I finally got to see Chris after I had been taken off the ventilator)!!

A week ago my sister Leah sat with me in the ICU while I was intubated and on a ventilator. I had no idea she was there…but God knew I needed her there. While she was with me, she started playing “Surrounded (Fight my battles)” and she said I started crying even though I was deeply sedated. She said I started nodding my head to the song. Y’all, I can’t shake it. All of it happened so quickly and I thought I wasn’t going to make it at one point…and then to hear this story. 😭 Jesus was with me at every single minute. I told a few people today I’m so deeply grateful for my life…and the recovery is very tough in a lot of ways. Thank you for praying for me!! Thank you for loving our family. We are so grateful. 💙
